    "abstract": "In this study, we build on previous research to understand the conditions within which the Wisdom of the Crowd (WoC) improves or worsens as a result of showing individuals the predictions of their peers. Our main novel contributions are: 1) a dataset of unprecedented size and detail; 2) we observe the novel effect of the importance of the unimodality of the social information shown to individuals: if one does not see only one clear peak in the distribution of the crowd's predictions, the WoC is worsened after social exposure; and 3) we estimate social learning weights that we use to show that there exists individuals who are much better at learning from the crowd and can be filtered to improve collective accuracy.",
